<article>
    <h1>Where to chill</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201225/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-25"><time>2020-12-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE STYLE WEEKEND</span>
        - <span role="byline">di&#xAD;no&#xAD;hadi@sph.com.sg Ed&#xAD;dino Ab&#xAD;dul Hadi</span>
    </section>

    <p>Ex-Bea­tle Paul McCart­ney’s (left) new­est al­bum – his 18th solo re­lease – is a pure McCart­ney ex­pe­ri­ence.</p>
    <p>Like on his pre­vi­ous two epony­mous re­leases, McCart­ney (1970) and McCart­ney II (1980), the 78-year-old wrote all the songs and played on all the in­stru­ments.</p>
    <p>Recorded in past months while un­der quar­an­tine, he has lost none of his knack for fetch­ing melodies, and there is vim and vigour in the new tunes.</p>
    <p>Pretty Boys, The Kiss Of Venus and al­bum closer Win­ter Bird/When Win­ter Comes have a folksy charm, while Slidin’ has shades of 1970s glam-rock sin­ga­longs.</p>
    <p>His voice is re­as­sur­ing on Find My Way, a song about com­fort­ing those in need, surely a balm in th­ese trou­bled times.</p>
    <p>But his play­ful­ness also comes to the fore on the rol­lick­ing La­va­tory Lil, per­haps a spir­i­tual suc­ces­sor to The Bea­tles’ Polythene Pam from their 1969 al­bum Abbey Road.</p>

